  "prompt_type": "cognitive",
  "prompt_text": "Explain the difference between TCP's three-way handshake and UDP's connectionless communication.",
  "response_text": "The main difference between TCP's three-way handshake and UDP's connectionless communication lies in the establishment and management of connections.\n\nTCP (Transmission Control Protocol) is a connection-oriented protocol, which means it establishes a connection between the sender and receiver before data is sent. This is achieved through a three-way handshake process:\n\n1.  **SYN (Sync) -** The client sends a SYN packet to the server, indicating its intention to establish a connection.\n2.  **SYN-ACK (Sync-Acknowledgment) -** The server responds with a SYN-ACK packet, acknowledging the client's request and sending its own SYN packet to establish the connection.\n3.  **ACK (Acknowledgment) -** The client sends an ACK packet to the server, confirming the connection is established.\n\nThis three-way handshake ensures that both parties are aware of the connection and can communicate effectively. Once the connection is established, data is sent in segments, and the receiver acknowledges each segment with an ACK packet. If any segment is lost or corrupted, the sender retransmits it, ensuring reliable data transfer.\n\nOn the other hand, UDP (User Datagram Protocol) is a connectionless protocol, which means it does not establish a connection before sending data. When a UDP client wants to send data to a server, it simply sends the data as a datagram, and the server receives it without any prior negotiation. If the datagram is lost or corrupted, it is not retransmitted, and the sender does not receive any acknowledgment.\n\nIn summary, TCP's three-way handshake establishes a reliable, connection-oriented communication, whereas UDP's connectionless communication relies on the application layer to handle errors and data transfer.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 8\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 6\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
